{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17598198","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17598198"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T11:34:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T11:34:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15449"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15449","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15449"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.04,0,0,0.92]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8140"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62914"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8140","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8140"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15449"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48365"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8127"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19727"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19731"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20503"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62914","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/62914"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe anal canal contains several important anatomical landmarks and can be affected by various pathological conditions. One such condition is an anal fissure. These can present acutely or chronically. Acute presentations are usually associated with intense pain, whereas chronic anal fissures are often painless and co-exist with other conditions such as Crohn\u0027s disease.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following statements best describes anal fissures?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["They only occur in patients with chronic constipation","They occur most commonly in the lateral positions","They only develop in patients with inflammatory bowel disease","They always heal spontaneously within two weeks","They are longitudinal tears extending from below the dentate line"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eanal fissure\u003C/strong\u003E is a longitudinal tear in the anal canal that typically extends from below the dentate line. Most fissures (90%) occur in the posterior midline, making the statement that they occur in the \u003Cstrong\u003Elateral positions\u003C/strong\u003E incorrect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile chronic constipation is a risk factor, it is incorrect to state that fissures \u003Cstrong\u003Eonly occur in patients with chronic constipation\u003C/strong\u003E. Similarly, while inflammatory bowel disease can be associated with anal fissures, they are not exclusive to patients with \u003Cstrong\u003Einflammatory bowel disease\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAnal fissures can become chronic and do not \u003Cstrong\u003Ealways heal spontaneously within two weeks\u003C/strong\u003E. They may require medical or surgical intervention for proper healing.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Anal fissures are longitudinal tears in the anal canal that typically occur in the posterior midline.","Anal fissures can be caused by trauma, constipation, or occur spontaneously.","The dentate (pectinate) line is an important anatomical landmark that divides the anal canal into upper and lower regions."],"references":["Steele SR, Madoff RD. Systematic review: the treatment of anal fissure. Aliment Pharmacol Ther. 2006 Jul 15;24(2):247-57. doi: 10.1111/j.1365-2036.2006.02990.x. PMID: 16842451.","Salati SA. Anal Fissure - an extensive update. Pol Przegl Chir. 2021 Mar 12;93(4):46-56. doi: 10.5604/01.3001.0014.7879. PMID: 34515649.","Jahnny B, Ashurst JV. Anal Fissures. [Updated 2022 Nov 14]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK526063/","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48365"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15449"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48365","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/48365"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-19T11:39:03+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-19T11:39:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8140"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62914"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (ide